{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_kfvnlygdsj1n_1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Foreword to the I Ching - By C. G. Jung\nURL: https://iging.com/intro/foreword.htm\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThis assumption involves a certain curious principle that I have termed synchronicity,[2]a concept that formulates a point of view diametrically opposed to that of causality. Since the latter is a merely statistical truth and not absolute, it is a sort of working hypothesis of how events evolve one out of another, whereas synchronicity takes the coincidence of events in space and time as meaning something more than mere chance, namely, a peculiar interdependence of objective events among themselves as well as with the subjective (psychic) states of the observer or observers.\n[...]\nsixty-four hexagrams of the*I Ching*\n[...]\nby which the\n[...]\nCausal connection\n[...]\ncan therefore be subjected\n[...]\nexperiment. Inasmuch as situations\n[...]\nrepeated, experimenting\n[...]\n]In the*I Ching*,\n[...]\nthe observer's\n[...]\ntext of the hexagram\n[...]\nof his psychic condition\n[...]\nof yarrow\n[...]\nbe in a given \"situation,\" inasmuch as anything happening in that\n[...]\nbelongs to it as\n[...]\nIf a handful of matches is thrown to\n[...]\nfloor, they\n[...]\ncharacteristic of that moment\n[...]\nBut such an obvious truth as this\n[...]\nis possible to read\n[...]\nand to verify\n[...]\ninterpretation, partly by\n[...]\ns knowledge of\n[...]\nsubjective and objective situation, partly by\n[...]\nIt is obviously not a procedure that appeals to a critical mind used to experimental verification of facts or to factual evidence\n[...]\nBut for someone who likes to look at\n[...]\nworld at the angle from which ancient China saw it, the*I Ching*may have some attraction.\n[...]\nIt would seem to me that on the basis of this example an unprejudiced reader would now be in a position to form at least a tentative judgment on the operation of the*I Ching*.[12]More cannot be expected from a simple introduction. If by means of this demonstration I have succeeded in elucidating the psychological phenomenology of the*I Ching*, I shall have carried out my purpose. As to the thousands of questions, doubts, and criticisms that this singular book stirs up -- I cannot answer these. The*I Ching*does not offer itself with proofs and results; it does not vaunt itself, nor is it easy to approach. Like a part of nature, it waits until it is discovered. It offers neither facts nor power, but for lovers of self-knowledge, of wisdom -- if there be such -- it seems to be the right book\n[...]\nTo one person its\n[...]\nas day;\n[...]\nas twilight; to a third, dark as night. He who is not pleased by it does not have to use it, and he who is against it is not obliged to find it true\n[...]\nLet it go forth\n[...]\nfor the benefit of those who can discern its\n[...]\n.> > C. G. JUNG\n\n---\n\nTitle: Social theory and social structure\nURL: https://search.worldcat.org/title/253949\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n# Social theory and social structure\n[...]\nAuthor:Robert King Merton(Author)\n[...]\nPrint Book,English,1968\n[...]\nEdition:1968 enlarged editionView all formats and editions\n[...]\nPublisher:Free Press,New York,1968\n[...]\nSocial theory and social structure\n[...]\npt. 1. On theoretical sociology. On the history and systematics of sociological theory\n[...]\nOn sociological theories of the middle range\n[...]\nManifest and latent functions\n[...]\nThe bearing of sociological theory on empirical research\n[...]\nThe bearing of empirical research on sociological theory\n[...]\npt. 2. Studies in social and cultural structure. Introduction\n[...]\nSocial structure and anomie\n[...]\nContinuities in the theory of social structure and anomie\n[...]\nBureaucratic structure and personality\n[...]\nin public bureaucracy\n[...]\nContributions to the theory of reference group behavior / with Alice S. Rossi\n[...]\nContinuities in the theory of reference groups and social structure\n[...]\nPatterns of influence: local and cosmopolitan influ\n[...]\nThe self-fulfilling prophecy\n[...]\npt. 3. The sociology of knowledge and mass communications. Introduction\n[...]\nThe sociology of knowledge\n[...]\nKarl Mannheim and the sociology of knowledge\n[...]\npt. 4. Studies in\n[...]\nsociology of science. Introduction\n\n---\n\nTitle: Synchronicity : An Acausal Connecting Principle (From Volume 8 of the Collected Works of C.G. Jung)\nURL: https://blog.umamaya.com/wp-content/gold/Jung/Synchronicity.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Jung, Carl G.(Author)\nHighlights:\nlective events that were about to take place in the world, led Jung to write the first manuscript of Liber Novus. He attempted to as certain to what extent the material in the\n[...]\nof his fantasies was also bound up with what was to happen in the world, and what this\n[...]\nof the individual and the collective\n[...]\n. Likewise, Jung's work on Liber Novus ended with the fateful arrival of the text of The Secret of the Golden Flower from Richard Wilhelm. For Jung, the pressing question was, how are such meaningful events— not linked by any apparent causal chains—possible? What does this say about the physical universe? In his memorial for Wilhelm, Jung used the word \"synchronicity\" to characterize the significance of the simultaneity of events that could not be causally linked. Jung gave such examples as the / Ching, the coincidence of Chinese and European periods of style, and astrology. 4 Only with the collabo ration of the Nobel Prize-winning physicist Wolfgang Pauli did Jung feel able to attempt such a far-reaching reformulation of the conception of the physical universe and its interdependence with the psyche, in a volume entitled The Interpretation of Nature and the Psyche 5 (which included a paper by Pauli on \"The Influence of Archetypal Ideas on the Scientific Theories of Kepler\"). Jung's work on synchronicity articulates a psychophysical ontology that could accommodate the experiences that underlie Liber Novus. Pauli and Jung self-consciously considered their work a new form of pre Cartesian natural philosophy, implicitly reinstating the antique conception of the correspondence between the physical and spiri tual worlds and hence bridging ancient and modern worldviews.\n[...]\nJung first used the term \"synchronicity\" only in 1930, in his \nmemorial address for Richard Wilhelm, 4 the translator of the \nI Ching, or Book of Changes. 5 Jung was seeking to explain the \nmodus operandi of the I Ching, which he had first come across \nin the early igzo's in an English translation by James Legge \n(1882) but, as he said, came to understand only when he read \nWilhelm's version.\n[...]\nHe referred to synchronicity again in his \"Tavistock Lec\n[...]\ntures\" in London,\n[...]\n35: \"...\n[...]\nif they were the same, and yet for us\n[...]\nare not/'\n[...]\nAgain in the\n[...]\nequated it with\n[...]\n. 7\n[...]\nYears later, in his foreword (written before 1950) to the Wil \nhelm/Baynes translation of the 7 Ching, Jung gave an exposi \ntion of the principle of synchronicity. 8 He was already preparing \nan extended monograph, but his first formal presentation of the\n[...]\ntheory was a brief lecture—his last—at the Eranos Conference\n[...]\nof 1951 at Ascona, Switzerland. 9 The monograph was published\n\n---\n\nTitle: Synchronicity - A Library Guide to Jung's Collected Works - Graduate Research Library at Pacifica Graduate Institute\nURL: https://pacifica.libguides.com/Jung/synchronicity\nPublished: 2026-05-29T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\ncitation (7th ed.)\n[...]\nth ed.)\n[...]\nForeword to the \"I-Ching\" (pp. 589-60)\n[...]\nAPA citation (7th ed.)\n[...]\nJung, C. G. (1969). Foreword to the \"I-Ching\" (C. F. Baynes, Trans.). In H. Read et al. (Eds.), The collected works of C. G. Jung: Vol. 11. Psychology and religion (2nd ed., pp. 589-608). Princeton University Press. (Original work published 1950) https://doi.org/10.1515/9781400850983.587\n[...]\n\"C. G. Jung had a lifelong interest in the paranormal that culminated in his influential theory of synchronicity. Combining extracts taken from the Collected Works; letters; the autobiographical Memories, Dreams, Reflections; and transcripts of seminars, Jung on Synchronicity and the Paranormal sets out clearly his seminal contribution to our understanding of this controversial area. In his Introduction, Roderick Main discusses Jung's encounters with and observations of the paranormal, the influences that contributed to his theory of synchronicity, and the central ideas of the theory itself. The selections include Jung's writings on mediumistic trance phenomena, spirits and hauntings, anomalous events in the development and practice of analytical psychology, and the divinatory techniques of astrology and the I Ching. The book also features Jung's most lucid account of his theory in the form of his short essay \"On Synchronicity,\" and a number of Jung's less-known writings on parapsychology, his astrological experiment, and the relationship between mind and body. Jung on Synchronicity and the Paranormal addresses subjects that were fundamental to Jung's personal and professional development. Probing deeply into the theory of synchronicity, Roderick Main clarifies issues that have long been a source of confusion to Jung's readers.\" [Read more]"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_function_p7vw6nqjp2z9_1","session_id":"e7c48987-b5d5-4f27-9d18-efac56ac5754","uuid":"e94e79b0-a3b1-4454-9808-10232551a497","timestamp":"2026-06-11T15:02:29.774Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Research I Ching 64 sources"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_kfvnlygdsj1n_2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Correspondences Part 13\nURL: http://www.smphillips.mysite.com/correspondences-13.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nReplacing each of the ten Sephiroth in the Tree of Life by another Tree of Life generates ten overlapping Trees of Life with 64 'Sephirothic levels' (SLs). 64 is the number value of Nogah, the Mundane Chakra of the Sephirah Hod, signifying mental activity and communication (see Table 1). 21 SLs (denoted by black dots) line the left-hand Pillar of Judgement, 21 SLs (denoted by white dots) line the right-hand Pillar of Mercy and 22 SLs (denoted by blue dots) line the central Pillar of Equilibrium. 21 is the number value of EHYEH (אהיה), the Godname of Kether.\n[...]\nCompare this with the 8×8 array of hexagrams that form the basis of the ancient Chinese I Ching system of divination. It consists of 64 hexagrams. 22 blue ones line two adjacent sides and a diagonal, 21 black hexagrams form a right-angled triangle on one side of the diagonal and 21 white hexagrams form a right-angled triangle on its opposite side. The hexagram (Chien) in the top left-hand corner of the table is a pair of \"Heaven\" trigrams:. This hexagram corresponds to the first SL, namely, Kether of the tenth Tree of Life. The hexagram (K'un) in the bottom right-hand corner is a pair of \"Earth\" trigrams:. It corresponds to the last SL, namely, Malkuth of the first Tree of Life, whose Mundane Chakra is the planet Earth. The 15 blue hexagrams on adjacent sides of the I Ching table correspond to the uppermost 15 SLs on the Pillar of Equilibrium. The remaining seven blue hexagrams on the diagonal correspond to the lowest seven SLs on this pillar that belong to the two lowest Trees. This 15:7 division of hexagrams reflects a 8:2 division of 10 overlapping Trees.\n[...]\nWe can take the correspondence between ten Trees of Life and the 64 hexagrams deeper by replacing each of the 64 SLs of the former by complete Trees of Life. The number of SLs in 64 overlapping Trees of Life is 388. Below Kether, Chokmah & Binah of the highest Tree are 385 SLs, where\n[...]\nThe 64 hexagrams correspond to the 64 pairs of triads of SLs in 64 Trees of Life, which express the 64 SLs in 10 Trees of Life representing the 10 Sephiroth of the Tree of Life.\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Hexagonal Geometry of the Tree of Life\nURL: https://hexnet.org/files/documents/hexgeometry.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Patrick Mulcahy\nHighlights:\nThis short treatise explores (using polyhex mathematics) the special relationship that exists between the kabbalistic Tree of Life diagram and the geometry of the simple hexagon. It reveals how the ten sefirot and the twenty two pathways of the Tree of Life are each individually and uniquely linked to the hexagonal form. The Hebrew alphabet is also shown to be esoterically associated with the geometry of the hexagon.\n[...]\nAs you may know, the pattern of the kabbalistic Tree of Life diagram is constructed using the geometry of the hexagon as its basis.\n[...]\nThe ten sefirot of the Tree diagram are positioned according to the principles of hexagonal geometry.\n[...]\nWhat may be new to you is the fact that the symbolism of the hexagon extends also to the ten individual sefirot and the twenty-two individual pathways of the Tree of Life.\n[...]\nThe hexagonal geometry of the ten sefirot and the twenty-two pathways is based on what is called 'polyhex mathematics'.\n[...]\nto the se\n[...]\nThe seven tetrahexes of the 4-hex group symbolise the seven lower sefirot of the Tree of Life.\n[...]\nThe twenty-two pentahexes correspond with the twenty-two pathways of the Tree of Life (and also the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet).\n[...]\nThe first four orders of polyhexes reflect the main body of the Tree diagram (i.e. the two primordial veils and the ten sefirot) while the fifth order of polyhexes is associated with the twenty-two pathways of the Tree of Life.\n[...]\nStar of David’).\n[...]\nOne major clue that helps us however, is that twelve of the twenty-two pentahexes are geometrically differentiated from the others and therefore appear to correspond with the twelve Simple letters of the Hebrew alphabet (i.e. as set forth in the book: The Sefer Yetzirah).\n[...]\nes, from 1-hex to 5-hex.\n[...]\nThese thirty-four polyhexes symbolise the two primordial veils, the ten sefirot, and the twenty-two pathways of the Tree of Life.\n[...]\nThe kabbalistic Tree of Life however, is traditionally ascribed only thirty-two component parts–i.e. the thirty-two ‘paths of wisdom’ of the Sefer Yetzirah.\n[...]\nThere are thus, two basic types of polyhex Tree of Life mandalas that can be assembled–a 34 polyhex type mandala, and a 32 polyhex type mandala.\n[...]\ntwenty-two pentahexes are\n[...]\nthe twenty-two\n[...]\nof Keter\n[...]\nt) are\n[...]\nThe figure comprehends the ten sefirot and the twenty-two pathways, but excludes the two primordial veils of Ain Sof (1-hex) and Aur (2-hex).\n[...]\nAgain, I have designed this figure (above) so as to contain all twenty-two of the Tree of Life pathway pentahexes.\n[...]\nI invented the word ‘hexagonagram’ to describe this figure because it combines both the hexagon and hexagram shapes.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Tree of life (Kabbalah) - Wikipedia\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_of_life_(Kabbalah)\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Tree of Life (Hebrew: עֵץ חַיִּים, ʿēṣ ḥayyim) is a symbolic diagram used in Jewish mystical traditions, especially in Kabbalah, to describe divine structure, creation, and the spiritual path of ascent.[1] It is usually referred to as the \"kabbalistic tree of life\" to distinguish it from the tree of life that appears alongside the tree of the knowledge of good and evil in the Genesis creation narrative as well as the archetypal tree of life found in many cultures.[2] It serves as both a conceptual framework and, in later Kabbalistic texts, a schematic diagram linking the sefirot, or divine emanations, to cosmology and human spiritual development.[1]\n[...]\nIn kabbalah, the nodes are called sefirot.[11] They are usually represented as circles and the paths (Hebrew: צִנּוֹר, romanized: ṣinnoroṯ) are usually represented as lines.[12] The nodes usually represent encompassing aspects of existence, God, or the human psyche.[13] The paths usually represent the relationship between the concepts ascribed to the spheres or a symbolic description of the requirements to go from one sphere to another.[13] The columns are usually symbolized as pillars.[14] These usually represent different kinds of moral values, electric charges, or types of ceremonial magic.[[[Wikipedia:Citing_sources|page needed]]]_8-1\">[[[Wikipedia:Citing_sources|page needed]]]-8\">[8]\n[...]\nThe sefirot are the ten spheres on the Tree of Life. Each sefirah (singular of sefirot) represents a different aspect of the Divine, as well as aspects of human consciousness and existence. These are, from top to bottom:[15]\n[...]\n516,\n[...]\n7 paths and, at the time, the concepts of 10 spheres and\n[...]\n2 letters were still distinct in\n[...]\nliterature.[19] In 157\n[...]\n, a version sketched by\n[...]\npaths appeared in\n[...]\nprint editions of\n[...]\nof the paths in\n[...]\ndescriptions are,\n[...]\n, in conflict describing different path arrangements\n[...]\npaths, though\n[...]\nand Netzach to Malkuth are\n[...]\nerav describes 22 paths\n[...]\nand 1\n[...]\nConcepts later associated with the Tree of Life draw in part on ideas found in Sefer Yetzirah, one of the earliest Jewish mystical texts, which presents creation as structured through sefirot and Hebrew letters functioning as organizing principles of cosmic order.[27] Although Sefer Yetzirah does not describe a fully articulated sefirotic system or a visual schema, it establishes a conceptual framework in which number, language, and divine activity are closely interconnected, providing an abstract, non-visual substrate for later Kabbalistic symbolism.[28]\n\n---\n\nTitle: Foundations of a postmodern cybernetics based on Kabbalah\nURL: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/220626476_Foundations_of_a_postmodern_cybernetics_based_on_Kabbalah\nPublished: 2024-10-22T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe TL of Kabbalah with the ten sefirot plus sefira Knowledge\n[...]\nThe TL as a graph where each of the sefirot nodes is described by a set of ten sub-sefirot organized also according to a sub-TL structure\n[...]\ndays, Kabbalah proposed the Tree of Life\n[...]\nAccording to Kabbalah,\n[...]\nand the process of its\n[...]\ncreation has ten fundamental general attributes/qualities calledsephirot, grouped in\n[...]\nthree categories (Menzi and Padeh, 2008):\n[...]\ncalled in Hebrewseﬁrot(plural, singular:seﬁra) which means counts, fundamental\n[...]\nthe tensephirot\n[...]\nunits or components are\n[...]\n22 lines based on the interactions between them and\n[...]\nbetween each of the three\n[...]\nlevels described above, in which thesesephi\n[...]\nSephirotin the TL are further organized into conﬁgurations ofseﬁrotcalledpartzuﬁm\n[...]\nThe TL contains three vertical axes: the right axis called the axis of Lovingkindness,\n[...]\nrawith the same name and theseﬁrotbelow and above it on the same\n[...]\naxis called the axis of Judgment,\n[...]\nThe TL structure is also the best description of the sub-attributes of a particular\n[...]\nThe TL becomes itself the basic building block for higher level structures called\n[...]\n“worlds” describing the four levels of existence, each of these worlds has itsown TL\n[...]\nstructure made of tenseﬁ\n[...]\nThe TL of the four worlds are interconnected in a cascade, from theseﬁraKingship of\n[...]\nThe TL and its microstructure taking into the account the sub-TL of each of its\n[...]\nseﬁrot\n[...]\nrepresented mathematically as a graph ﬁbration(Boldi and Vigna, 2002\n[...]\nIn our case, the ﬁbre is the sub-TL of eachseﬁrahin\n[...]\nTL acting as ﬁbre\n[...]\nover eachseﬁraof the TL base space with the natural projection (\n[...]\nThe ﬁbration is trivial and is in fact a Cartesian product of graphs\n[...]\nthe TL deﬁnes\n[...]\nTL£TL between the graph of the TL and itself, seen as a model for the sub-TL of each\n[...]\nThe TL, seen as a graph withseﬁrotas nodes and their 22 interconnections as arcs\n[...]\nThe TL as a graph can also be seen as generating its own free category, a diagram\n[...]\ngenerated categoryC(TL) having as objects theseﬁrotseen each, in its turn, as a graph\n[...]\nor set of ten states given by eachseﬁra\n[...]\nssub-TL (Figure 2).\n[...]\nThe morphisms betweenseﬁrot, indicated by the edges of the TL, are deﬁned as\n[...]\nmappings between the corresponding graphs or sets of ten states given by the sub-TL\n[...]\nof eachseﬁra. In addition, we add identity morphismsfor eachseﬁra, mappingeach\n[...]\net of sub-seﬁrotinto itself, seen as self-loops or identity arcs. The composition\n[...]\nThe tree has three axes: right corresponding to acceptance and Lovingkindness,"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_function_p7vw6nqjp2z9_1","session_id":"e7c48987-b5d5-4f27-9d18-efac56ac5754","uuid":"4e85e9b3-2ba6-44f8-8d83-8e3b09c0eead","timestamp":"2026-06-11T15:02:29.887Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Research I Ching 64 sources"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_kfvnlygdsj1n_4","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: ‎Hexagram Dreams: I Ching Guide App - App Store\nURL: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/i-ching-ai-oracle-journal/id6480458200\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nI Ching companion. Build a personal reflection journal, use our coach to ask better questions and AI for a custom reading interpretation. Track your patterns over time with advanced analytics no other I Ching app offers, and build a consistent practice you'll actually keep. Use the I Ching as a daily reflection practice. Cast with intention. Explore the meaning. Make decisions with perspective. Whether it's a relationship, a career crossroads, or a feeling you can't quite name, the I Ching helps you slow down and see your situation from a wiser angle. HOW IT WORKS ◆ Focus on your question - write down your concern you want clarity on. The quality of your question shapes the quality of your reading. ◆ Cast your hexagram - use the traditional three-coin method line by line, or use automatic casting for a faster read. ◆ Interpret your reading - explore the primary hexagram, changing lines, and the resulting hexagram. ◆ Reflect and save - add personal notes, tag your reading, and revisit it later to see how things unfolded. Some of the questions you can ask: ◆ What matters most right now? ◆ How do I handle tension with a friend or partner? ◆ What is the best next step for my career or project? ◆ What am I not seeing in this situation? ◆ How can I approach this change with less fear? ◆ What should I focus on this week to feel more grounded? WHAT MAKES HEXAGRAM DREAMS DIFFERENT ◆ Advanced analytics - see which of the 64 hexagrams you encounter most, track your five element balance and trigram distribution, spot recurring transformation pairs, and discover your reading rhythm with a weekly heatmap. Monitor your streak, collection progress, and how your practice evolves over time. No other I Ching app gives you this depth of insight. ◆ Authentic casting - experience the traditional three-coin toss one line at a time, with clear visual guidance at each step. Designed for a mindful, intentional experience. ◆ Personal Reflection journal - revisit past readings and see how your interpretations compare to real outcomes. ◆ Practice reminders - set daily or weekly reminders to build a consistent I Ching reflection habit and maintain your streak. ◆ AI-assisted interpretation - get context-aware insight based on your specific question, hexagram, and changing lines. A thoughtful companion to your own reflection. ◆ Complete hexagram library - all 64 hexagrams with detailed descriptions, core themes, and practical guidance. ◆ Changing lines explained - understand how movement shapes the reading, what to pay attention to, and how it relates to your situation. ◆ Question Coach - it's important how you ask a question. Use our coach to get question ideas, refine your questions, and receive related\n\n---\n\nTitle: ‎Hexagram Dreams: I Ching Guide App - App Store\nURL: https://apps.apple.com/au/app/i-ching-ai-oracle-journal/id6480458200\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nI Ching companion. Build a personal reflection journal, use our coach to ask better questions and AI for a custom reading interpretation. Track your patterns over time with advanced analytics no other I Ching app offers, and build a consistent practice you'll actually keep. Use the I Ching as a daily reflection practice. Cast with intention. Explore the meaning. Make decisions with perspective. Whether it's a relationship, a career crossroads, or a feeling you can't quite name, the I Ching helps you slow down and see your situation from a wiser angle. HOW IT WORKS ◆ Focus on your question - write down your concern you want clarity on. The quality of your question shapes the quality of your reading. ◆ Cast your hexagram - use the traditional three-coin method 